Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Businesses balk at tax proposals. We're not hearing much praise from the business community for President Obama's tax proposals in the State of the Union address. Tom Deas, treasurer of fertilizer maker FMC Corp., told us the president's call for a minimum tax on overseas profits could make American multinationals less competitive. "If it's demonstrably better for a U.S. company that makes products overseas to place factories near their customers," it shouldn't be penalized for making that business decision, he said. Snap-On CEO Nicholas Pinchuk told the Journal's John Bussey that he liked the proposal to ease the tax burden for domestic manufacturers, but Obama "seemed to mention several new regulations even as he spoke of reduction." And the former CFO of a large consumer products company suggested that rather than penalizing companies for offshoring jobs, the government should use tax policy to incentivize job creation in the U.S. "Our government must recognize we live in a world economy, not a U.S. economy," he said.
That's a message Corporate America is going to have to make forcefully next month when the Treasury Department outlines corporate-tax code changes. The WSJ says the administration understands the "political challenges of crafting tax changes. But part of their strategy is to begin negotiations with Republicans and business groups now so changes might be added at the end of the year when Congress decides how to address the expiring Bush-era tax cuts."

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways

Engineering firm Jacobs Engineering Group, which is having its annual shareholders' meeting in Pasadena, California on Thursday, will be the first big firm in the 2012 proxy season to try to convince shareholders to agree with its compensation packages. Should it not, that will make it two consecutive failures for its say-on-pay votes.
The advisory say-on-pay vote, required at large public companies by the Dodd-Frank reform law for the first time last year, has been criticized as toothless, but proxy experts say the exercise has sharpened the focus of compensation committees on poor pay practices, and increased communication between boards and shareholders about compensation.

#text: Blockbuster

lost $15.6 million, or 9 cents a share, improving over the loss of $27.9 million, or 16 cents a share, a year earlier. Excluding amortization charges, the retailer posted cash earnings of $26.3 million, or 15 cents a share, compared with $13.8 million, or 8 cents a share, last year. Analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial were looking for Blockbuster to report cash earnings of 10 cents a share, on average. Shares fell $1.08 to close at $17.40.

#text: Xicor Inc.

shares plunged 64 percent Tuesday
            after the company said second-quarter earnings will come in below First Call's average
            estimate of 15 cents a share. The firm said recent bookings show second-quarter revenue
            tracking flat or lower from the first quarter's $32.1 million. Citing the earnings
            shortfall, Xicor said Bruce Gray has resigned as the company's president. Shares lost 11
            11/16 to close at 6 11/16.
